Add more explanation

Do the constructions here really all need `EnoughInjectives`, or does it suffice to mostly work with an injective hull for some fixed object, until the very end where you prove that you can transfer `EnoughInjectives` along the adjunction?
Indeed, assuming just an injective hull is sufficient

It would be nice to state separately that if `M : â„¬` is injective, then `R.obj M` is also injective (under the assumption that `L` preserves monomorphisms). (This is related to `CategoryTheory.LiftingProperties.Adjunction`, even though it may not be necessary to use that...) Then, the core argument here seems to be that if `A : ð’œ`, and `L.obj A` embeds in an (injective) object `I : â„¬`, then the adjoint map `A âŸ¶ R.obj I` is also a mono (essentially what you prove in `mono_toUnder`, but there is a more direct proof relying directly on the adjunction, without the need to introduce the kernel). It seems to me that doing so would significantly shorten the length of the code.
by avoiding `kernel`, it turns out assuming abelian-ness of categories are unnecessary! Thanks

Could this instance ever fire? I think the instance should use `UnivLE`, otherwise we should make it a def.

Indeed, the following does **not** work
```lean
instance : EnoughInjectives (ModuleCat.{u, u} R) := inferInstance
```
where `R` lives in universe `u` as well
Does this mean `ModuleCat.restrictCoextendScalarsAdj` need to use `UnivLE` also?

> Indeed, the following does **not** work
```lean
instance : EnoughInjectives (ModuleCat.{u, u} R) := inferInstance
```
> where `R` lives in universe `u` as well

Yeah, Lean 4 refuses to unify `max u v` with `u` because `v` can be either `0` or `u`. This `{u,u}` version could be an instance (as well as `{u+1, u}`, `{u, 0}`, but they will subsumed by the instance with UnivLE).

> Does this mean `ModuleCat.restrictCoextendScalarsAdj` need to use `UnivLE` also?

Not necessarily, as you can specify the universes explicitly when using it.

Can you elaborate please, I tried the following
```lean
instance [UnivLE.{u, v}] : EnoughInjectives (ModuleCat.{v, u} R) := 
  EnoughInjectives.of_adjunction (ModuleCat.restrictCoextendScalarsAdj.{v, 0, u} (algebraMap â„¤ R))
```
Looks like that Lean 4 doesn't see `Type v` and `Type {max v u}` are the same.

A minimal example is perhaps this:
```lean
example [UnivLE.{u, v}] : ModuleCat.{v} â„¤ â¥¤ ModuleCat.{v, u} R :=
  ModuleCat.coextendScalars.{0, u, v} (algebraMap â„¤ R)
```
does not compile

`UnivLE.{u, v}` says every type in universe u is in bijection with some type in universe v (after my refactor #8556). It doesn't give you `v = max u w` for some `w` (and I don't think it's currently possible to state this equality as a proposition in Lean). It seems a bit nontrival to transfer EnoughInjectives from `max u v` to `UnivLE`, so I suggest you just leave it as a `def` for now and manually specify the universes when you want to use it.
(Edit: it should be relatively easy using the injectivity criterion [Module.Baer](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Module/Injective.html#Module.Baer), which is independent of the universe, so we can transfer enough injectives in the universe u of R to another universe v satisfying `UnivLE.{u,v}`.)
Thanks for the suggestion. I have changed instance to a def. I realized that we know `Module.Baer` implies injectivity but not the otherway around (fixed in #8587).
This one can be generalized to [F.ReflectsMonomorphisms] as I did in my commit. Should we keep this?
I think we should just keep the version with `[F.ReflectsMonomorphisms]`
That version has to live in the file EpiMono though, where ReflectsMonomorphisms is defined.
